<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 21. Working with the Skirt Pattern.</h1>
<p><strong>I am about to start working on the skirt </strong>which was chosen to suit my client�s taste and to match the circumstances. The wedding ceremony will take place on the seashore, which means she will wear it both with high-heel shoes and barefooted.</p>
<p>This book comes with a skirt pattern and a ruffles layout made for a particular size. I would therefore like to tell you how I made it and what to do if your client�s size is different.</p>
<p><strong>The pattern was based on a basic bell-shaped skirt pattern. </strong>Such patterns are rather common.</p>
<p><strong>Below is the pattern I started from. I will show you the whole process so you can repeat it yourself. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The first thing I did was adjust it to my client�s measurements. </strong>I measured the pattern along the waistline, the stomach line (marked at a particular distance from the waistline), and the hip line. I determined how much I needed to remove (the pattern had to be made smaller in my client�s case) and I did accordingly straight away.</p>
<p><strong>I re-drew the pattern in my client�s size. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Since the skirt will feature a wide waistband resembling a waist cincher, I re-draw the top line 6cm lower than it was and mark the point of intersection with the side seam line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>The back and the front of this skirt are absolutely identical. <strong>I put the front piece next to the back piece aligning their side seam lines. </strong>I lower the top line of the front piece by the same 6cm and then by another 3cm in the middle as implied by the style of the skirt. There will be a downward corner in the middle of the waistband at the front of the skirt.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>After comparing the two pieces, I divide the angle between them in half by drawing a bisector. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark the train length along the central edge of the back. </strong>I decided to make it 50cm plus another 10cm for a bottom ruffle, which makes a total length of 60cm.</p>
<p><strong>In addition, I mark the side length of the skirt down from the waistline in accordance with my client�s measurement. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Then I draw the bottom line of the back piece by connecting the bottom side seam point with the bottom point of the train in a smooth curve. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I erase all excess lines and get a pattern of the back of the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I move to the front half of the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I mark 35cm from the waistline along the front line and 30cm along the princess seam line and connect the two points with a half-circle line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I draw a new princess seam line. It starts as a curved line and then goes straight, crosses the side seam line of the back piece about 10cm from its bottom point, and blends smoothly with the train line. I don�t want the skirt to be way too open at the front so I decided to partially cover up the sides and make a smooth transition to the back of the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>What I have now is a garment made of a front piece and a large back piece. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I feel like dividing the large back piece in two parts. </strong>I draw a straight line. Now there is a back piece and a separate side piece.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Here is the resulting pattern. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I add seam allowances along all sewing lines, as well as along the top and the bottom lines. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The skirt pattern is ready and now I can think over how and in what order to sew ruffles on it (it depends on how full you want the skirt to be). </strong>I have chosen one of the layouts I have in stock and printed it out. I will probably adjust it a little in the process.</p>
<p><strong>The skirt features a train, it is short at the front, and it is framed by ruffles. </strong>It could have been cut as a single piece or as two parts (front and back) but I have purposely divided the pattern in gores instead.</p>
<p><strong>This time I will use a different sewing and cutting technique. </strong>Please note that the direction of the lengthwise grain is marked on the pattern. The fold line of the front piece runs parallel to the lengthwise grain and so does the central back seam line. What concerns the side piece, the lengthwise grain may run parallel to the front edge or parallel to the princess seam line. I have chosen the latter.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>You always need to decide on the width and the shape of your ruffles before sewing them on the skirt. </strong>Moreover, you need to keep in mind that the ruffles at the bottom of the skirt must be larger than the ruffles at the top of it.</p>
<p><strong>My ruffles will be made of thin voile curtain fabric. </strong>The largest will have a width of 11cm and the smallest - a width of 7cm. I will gradually go from the largest to the smallest ruffles and try to make the transition as smooth as possible. The distance between the bottom ruffles will be a little bigger than between the top ruffles. The ruffles at the top of the skirt need to be positioned with smaller intervals because of their smaller size.</p>
<p><strong>I also need to account for the curved train line in the layout.</strong> I purposely marked the bottom line on the skirt pattern to know where exactly the transition to the train begins, i.e. to know what part of the skirt hangs vertically and what part starts settling upon the floor. This will affect the layout: it is highly recommended to position ruffles parallel to the floor on the part of the skirt that hangs vertically whereas on the train they can be positioned in half-circle rows from one edge to the other.</p>
<p><strong>I start drawing the layout without paying attention to the princess seam line which joins two separate parts of the skirt.</strong> Before we continue, I would like to show schematically and explain how I made the layout enclosed with this book.</p>
<p><strong>I start drawing ruffle guidelines on the skirt pattern. </strong>At first, I draw them at an angle and with bigger intervals along the central back seam line than along the front line. You can see it in the draft below.</p>
<p>I will put additional shorter ruffles in-between these main ruffles. The ruffles become horizontal as I move closer to the top of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong>This is the initial layout I made. </strong></p>
<p>The bottom ruffles are positioned with 2.5 - 3cm intervals which gradually narrow down to 1.5cm as the ruffles go up.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I am satisfied with the configuration of the guidelines. I am also happy with their length and now I can start marking guidelines for vertical ruffles.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Vertical ruffles will run along the princess seam, the front edge of the skirt, and the back edge of the skirt. </strong>They will be positioned with 1.5cm intervals.</p>
<p><strong>In addition, I feel like slightly changing the existing layout by putting some more ruffles on the train. They will radiate from the central back seam. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>And now I would like to say a couple of words about the ruffles themselves. </strong>Considering that the wedding ceremony will take place on the seashore, I want these ruffles to resemble sea waves. If you look at the supplementary materials enclosed with the book, you will see <strong>two ruffle patterns</strong>: the first type is a plain circle (I will only use it for the vertical ruffles) and the second type is a circle with wavy edges (it will be used for the horizontal ruffles).</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Please note that the slit in the ruffle should be cut at 45 degrees to get bias edges. </strong>I would not recommend you make those edges rounded because it will decrease the fullness of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong>I hope I have managed to convince you that you must think over every little detail before you start working on the skirt. </strong>I go through all work stages in my head before getting down to sewing.</p>
<p><strong>How to determine the length of each ruffle? </strong>You must have already noticed that all guidelines have different lengths. It varies from 7cm up to 35cm. To make things easier, I purposely cut all ruffles with the same diameter of the inner circle regardless of their width. What concerns the length, I will simply trim each ruffle according to the length of the corresponding guideline.</p>
<p><strong>I mark lines at 1cm intervals along the perimeter of the inner circle. It will be easier to adjust the length of the ruffle this way. </strong>The longest guideline is 18.5cm. Whenever I need a shorter ruffle, I will simply trim it in accordance with these small lines without having to measure anything. Remember to always trim it on the bias.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2021.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The width of the vertical ruffles will be proportionate to the width of the horizontal ruffles in the same area of the skirt. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I tried to make the layout as simple as possible: </strong>areas with ruffles of different widths are marked by different colours and the actual widths of vertical and horizontal ruffles are marked in centimeters.</p>
<p><strong>Summing up, I have introduced you to a new sewing technique by splitting the skirt in gores. </strong>There have been courses dedicated to sewing skirts at the Corset Academy but all of them involved working with rather large pieces of fabric, which is very awkward when you need to put ruffles on the skirt. It is a lot easier to sew ruffles on a skirt made of gores when you work with relatively narrow pieces of fabric. Even a household sewing machine can cope with the task. Moreover, dividing a skirt pattern in gores allows you to reinforce the princess seams with soft Rigilene boning to help the garment hold its shape and volume better.</p>
<p>I am sure you will get your own ideas as soon as you get down to work. You will probably find some new skirt styles and see the technique of sewing sophisticated wedding skirts in a whole new light.</p>
<p><strong>There is still a long way before us! Let us walk it together! </strong></p>

